Digital Parenting

"Having the digital knowledge and the skills to move in the digital world, without suffering the dangers, is not a matter of age, but of education and learning, that is, digital literacy. It is a serious responsibility towards the new generations and a complex challenge for which the adults (parents, teachers, psychologists, or educators) do not feel prepared."


- Loredana Benedetto &

Massimo Ingrassia

Department of Clinical & Experimental Medicine

University of Messina, Italy

Online Workshop - Register Now

As a parent, I am very technology loving and always encourage my children to use it. By profession, I have been connected to the computer industry for more than 20 years. I have lived and worked in the Silicon Valley of California, USA. I know the benefits and dangers of the software and internet technology, especially if it is unmonitored and unregulated.

Today's smartphone and tablets are actually full functioning computers in smaller form. The apps and websites in them are a great resource and children can learn from and enjoy them greatly. However, just like any technology, apps and websites can be extremely harmful to children. Many of these apps, games and websites are made by criminals to spy on children, communicate with children, obtain their location and other details and ultimately, commit a crime, like kidnapping or worse. It is extremely important to constantly monitor the digital devices used by children.

Then there is this issue about digital devices and its effects on children's health. Too much use has proven negative effects to the eyes, thinking, sleep patterns, eating disorders and to the overall health of the children. Children will always be children and expecting even teenagers to self manage their time on their smartphones, tablets or laptops will never end well. It is extremely important to constantly regulate the digital devices used by children.

Online Workshop - Register Now

After years of searching, testing, trial and error, I found the perfect solution to monitor and regulate my children's digital devices. Most importantly, the process has to be quick, easy and mostly automatic. I have spoken to other parents about their children's use of digital technology and find we are all in the same boat. We want the best for our children, but many of us don't exactly know how to protect our children from the dangers of digital devices. On one such conversation, a father suggested that I may consider providing formal training to other parents on the solution I perfected.

The structure of this training or knowledge exchange should be in the form of an online workshop where we parents learn from each other, discuss the issues, practice and finally apply the solution, customizing it to the individual needs of us and our children.

How to set a phone or PC to supervise your child's phone, tablet and laptop.

Individually approve or ban app downloads and website visits.

Set daily use time per app. Set time to auto lock or unlock the device.

Track the exact location of your child on Google Maps.

Age restrict App Store search and enforce Safe Search on Google and Youtube.

Two day workshop for non technical parents. Day one on Android and day two on Windows.

View daily, weekly and monthly usage information per child per app.
